result.execSummary:
The defendant Demario Latrell Rucker was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Intimidate Witness/Person Charged/Felony [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.43(7).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Demario Latrell Rucker not in court.  Evan Glaberson appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Case held over from  12/19/2014.  Court is in receipt of e-mail from agent.  Defendant is in absconder status.  Court ordered 120 DAYS stayed condition time imposed FORTHWITH. Signed & Filed, Order for Condition Time.

Defendant Demario Latrell Rucker in court with attorney Terese M. Dick.  Matthew G. Puthukulam appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded. Statements by parties and defendant. Court reviewed photos and returned to state. Additional statements by defendant's sister.
AS TO COUNT 1
The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 6 YEARS, consecutive, credit for 42 DAYS time served, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 2 YEARS, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 4 YEARS. Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 3 YEARS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION
-Serve 120 DAYS in the House of Correction as Condition Time, STAYED pending review.
-Batterers Intervention program.
-Parenting classes.
-Mental health evaluation, take all prescribed medications.
-AODA assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
-Absolute sobriety, random urine screens.
-Treatment and/or counseling as determined by agent.
-No contact with victim, unless approve by court or agent, except for third party contact as approved by agent.
-Obtain/maintain employment, or proof of SSI/SSDI.
-No contact with firearms.
-Court ordered the defendant to pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, and surcharges to be paid during probation, if revoked to be paid from 25% of prison funds during initial confinement and then to be collected during extended supervision, failure to pay will result in a civil judgment. 
-Court WAIVED all NON-Mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges.
-Provide DNA Sample.
-Restitution set at ZERO.

*Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program OR the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.
*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised defendant of penalties for violation of NO CONTACT ORDER.
*Court advised due to DV conviction under federal law the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
*Court allows transfer of probation to Georgia, if accepted.

Filed: Pretrial Sentence Credit, Notice of Right to Seek Post-Conviction Relief, Memorandum of Conditions of Probation, Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence  Probation Review Hearing scheduled for December 19, 2014 at 01:30 pm.
Received & Filed, Amended Information (reflects oral amendments previously made to Count 1)

AS TO COUNT 2
Pursuant to plea negotiations, on a motion of the state the court ordered Count 2 Dismissed, But Read In.
AS TO COUNT 1 AS AMENDED
Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Court advised defendant of penalties for violation of NO CONTACT ORDER. Court advised that under 48 USC Section 922(g)(9) the defendant is prohibited from possession of a firearm and/or ammunition after conviction of a crime of domestic violence. Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored. Discussion regarding defendant's communication privileges. Court did NOT modify restriction, but will allow for in person visitation from defendant's mother if order is submitted to the court. Case adjourned to branch 23 for Sentencing.
